Containers are widely used in real-world applications across industries.

For example, Netflix uses containers to deploy microservices that handle streaming, recommendations, and user data.

Another example is an e-commerce platform where different services like payment, inventory, and user authentication run in separate containers.

A real-life use case is DevOps pipelines where containers are used to build, test, and deploy applications consistently.

Another example is machine learning workflows where models are packaged into containers for deployment.

These examples show how containers enable scalability, flexibility, and faster delivery.
